Habermas argues that when speakers are communicating successfully, they will have to defend their meaning by using these four claims.
BULLET::::1. That they have "uttered something" understandably — or "their statements are intelligible";
BULLET::::2. That they have given other people "something to understand" — or are speaking "something true";
BULLET::::3. That "the speaker" is therefore understandable — or their "intentions are recognized and appreciated" for what they are; and,
BULLET::::4. That they have come to an understanding "with another person" — or, they have used "words that both actors can agree upon". (1979:4)

One way to grasp this idea is to take an inventory of the ways in which an attempt at communication can misfire, the ways a speech act can fail. A hearer may reject the offering of a speech act on the grounds that it is invalid because it:
BULLET::::1. presupposes or explicates states of affairs which are not the case (IT);
BULLET::::2. does not conform to accepted normative expectations (WE);
BULLET::::3. raises doubts about the intentions or sincerity of the speaker (I).
Of course, from this it follows that a hearer who accepts the offering of a speech act does so on the grounds that it is valid because it:
BULLET::::1. presupposes or explicates states of affairs that are true (IT);
BULLET::::2. conforms to accepted normative expectations (WE);
BULLET::::3. raises no doubts concerning the intentions or sincerity of the speaker (I).
